		<pb n="1"/>
			<p><addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>London</placeName> <date>30 April 1851</date></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">I duly received your favor of <date>31st</date> Ulto.<lb/> &#38; notice your observations in reply to my remarks on the arrangement<lb/> made for the Conciliator sent you&#44; certainly I did not know of your having<lb/> paid duty freight &#38;c for except three copies sent through <persName>Chapman</persName> the others<lb/> were forwarded by private hands&#44; but nothing more need be said on that<lb/> subject as I accepted of your proposal &#38; which as I advised you <persName>Mrs. Joel</persName><lb/> settled for the <date>22 Jany</date>. Altho&#39; as the author you may set a high value on your<lb/> Occident still you must remember that except for some good Sermons it is not inter<lb/>&#45;esting to a European as the news in it from this part of the world is stale to them<lb/> &#38; any thing of congregational matters that happen in the <placeName>West</placeName> is immediately inser<lb/>ted in the journals here &#38; appear long before the Occident is seen as to its nominal<lb/> value please to recollect when I sent you the Conciliator the price was 25&#47; &#38; my<lb/> History is selling &#64;12&#47; which together is equal to 5 vol. of the Occident it could be of<lb/> no use to me in my literary pursuits therefore it cannot be supposed I would lay out<lb/> money to purchase it. I have the first volume which my son in <placeName>Jamaica</placeName> sent me &#38;<lb/> had you have presented me with the others should have been put to the <sic>expence</sic> of<lb/> having them bound which I now save&#44; but as you make it a matter of dollars &#38; cents<lb/> I have no objection to treat it in the same way &#38; if you like it will give <persName>Mrs Joel</persName> five<lb/> <hi rend="underline">unbound</hi> copies of the Conciliator for the 7 last volumes of your Occident on no other<lb/> terms would I add it to my already extensive library.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I thank you for your kind intention towards my recommendation of <persName>Mr Moraes</persName><lb/> who I feel convinced you will find grateful for any thing you may do for him &#38; equally<lb/> so that you will be pleased with him as you get better acquainted with him.<lb/> In reiterating towards yourself your kind expressions to me I remain</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">Sincerely Yours</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">E H Lindo</persName></p>
			<p>I have just learned that <persName>Mr. M</persName> has been elected<lb/> &#38; to my great surprise that you were a candidate<lb/> for I had heard that you had refused the office</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><addressee>Revd. Mr. I. Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          
